together daily, her previous training helping her pick up the subtleties of the martial combat easier.  He had never had a pupil that learned as quickly.  Soon he began to forget to worry about how she would react to him touching her or moving with her to teach her a lesson.<br>
<br>
In this skill she truly found a fighting form that she enjoyed.  Her eyes sparkled as she learned and her new moves and often at night when the temple came alive with dancing and music you could see her adding a new step to her dances that must have come from her lessons.  Her vibrancy and self-assurance added more to her beauty daily.  Brenton had no doubts now in having her learn from Xanthala before having Arean arrive.<br>
<br>
One night he was watching the dancers and the crowd while he played and he noticed something.  Arean watched Kestri very closely, once a man from the town was in the temple and was talking to her after a dance and Arean had almost left his seat and then sat back down looking dazed.  It seemed that Xanthala had noticed it too and went to talk to him.<br>
<br>
That night Brenton sought out Xan after people had headed to bed.  “Do we have a problem Xan?”  She tossed her head back and laughed, “not the one you though we would have, that’s for sure.”<br>
<br>
“So Kes isn’t infatuated?” his voice deep with concern.  Xanthala just took his hand and leads him to the garden.<br>
<br>
There are two figures in the garden and it is not hard to tell who they are.  The small young woman and the well-built monk.  Their voices carry to the older two.<br>
<br>
“But Kes, I don’t understand.” His voice quiet and controlled.  “I am in love with you.  You are strong, beautiful and a wonderful woman.”<br>
<br>
She turned from him and stayed quiet.  He walked to her and put his arms around her, “Kestri, I have been around women all over this land and have never met a woman like you.  When I first met you I worried that you would love me, now I am scared to death that you don’t.”<br>
<br>
Softly she spoke and Brenton could sense her control of her gift in his mind.  He recognized the tune and what she was doing.  She was tempering her speech with a lulling melody so that Arean would not be hurt.  “Arean, my friend, my teacher.  I have a destiny to fulfill.  The lady has visited me and told me of this and I know that now is not my time for love.  There are many people out in the world that will need me, and my music.  And someday I hope to find the man for me, but that is not in Her plan right now.”<br>
<br>
She turned back to him, comforted in his arms, her eyes were brimming with tears, “You are the first man that I have cared about other than Brenton, but you are not the one I was meant for.  I know that someday I will find him, but I cannot settle for anyone other than the Lady has promised me.  I am sorry.”  She laid a small hand on his cheek then stepped back and walked away.  The power of her music leaving with her, his shoulders slump forward in grief.<br>
